library(dplyr)

pf.fc_by_age_gender <- 
  pf %>%
  filter(!is.na(gender)) %>%
  group_by(age, gender) %>%
  summarise(friend_count_mean = mean(friend_count),
            friend_count_median = median(friend_count),
            n<- n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(age)

head(pf.fc_by_age_gender)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##     age gender friend_count_mean friend_count_median `n <- n()`
##   <int> <fct>              <dbl>               <dbl>      <int>
## 1    13 female              259.               148          193
## 2    13 male                102.                55          291
## 3    14 female              362.               224          847
## 4    14 male                164.                92.5       1078
## 5    15 female              539.               276         1139
## 6    15 male                201.               106.        1478

Plotting Conditional Summaries

ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count_median),
       data = pf.fc_by_age_gender) +
  geom_line(aes(color = gender))

#install.packages('reshape2')
library(reshape2)

pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide <- dcast(pf.fc_by_age_gender,
                                  age ~ gender,
                                  value.var = 'friend_count_median')

Third Quantitative Variable

Notes:

pf$year_joined <- floor(2014 - pf$tenure/365)

Cut a Variable

Notes: the cut function is useful for making discrete variables from continuous or nomerical ones.

pf$year_joined.bucket <- cut(pf$year_joined, c(2004, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2014))

Plotting it All Together

ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(year_joined.bucket))) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket), stat = 'summary', fun.y = median)

Plot the Grand Mean

Notes: plot the mean instead of the median

ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(year_joined.bucket))) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket), stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean) +
  geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean, linetype = 2)

Friending Rate

Notes: we want to see how many friends does a user have for each day since starting using facebook.

with(subset(pf, tenure >= 1), summary(friend_count/tenure))
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
##   0.0000   0.0775   0.2205   0.6096   0.5658 417.0000

Friendships Initiated

What is the median friend rate? 0.2205

What is the maximum friend rate? 417

ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure >= 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket), stat = 'summary', fun.y = median)

Bias-Variance Tradeoff Revisited

Notes: we can adjust the noise from the last graph by bending our x-axis differently.

ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure >= 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = year_joined.bucket))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),stat = 'summary',
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 30 * round(tenure / 30), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 90 * round(tenure / 90), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

Introducing the Yogurt Data Set

Notes: the facebook data has one row per individual, on the other hand, Yogurt data has many rows per household, one for each purchase occasion.

Histograms Revisited

Notes: First, convert id from integer into factor. Second, create a histogram of the Yogurt prices.

Heat Maps

nci <- read.table("nci.tsv")
colnames(nci) <- c(1:64)
nci.long.samp <- melt(as.matrix(nci[1:200,]))
names(nci.long.samp) <- c("gene", "case", "value")
head(nci.long.samp)
##   gene case  value
## 1    1    1  0.300
## 2    2    1  1.180
## 3    3    1  0.550
## 4    4    1  1.140

ggplot(aes(y = gene, x = case, fill = value),
  data = nci.long.samp) +
  geom_tile() +
